-- Eastern U.S. Power Advances as Hotter Weather Boosts Cooling
-- B y   M a r i o   P a r k e r
-- 2013-07-05T18:53:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-05/eastern-u-s-power-advances-as-hotter-weather-boosts-cooling.html
Spot wholesale electricity in  New
York  City and Boston gained as hotter weather spurred demand to
use air conditioners for cooling.  The high temperature in Boston today may be 96 degrees
Fahrenheit (36 Celsius), 15 above normal, according to
AccuWeather Inc. in  State College , Pennsylvania. New York may
rise to 92 degrees, 8 above normal.  Spot electricity in Boston jumped 61 percent to $169.98 a
megawatt-hour during the hour ended at 1 p.m. from the same time
yesterday, according to grid data compiled by Bloomberg. Power
prices in New York gained 37 percent to $83.34.  Spot electricity at PJM Interconnection LLC’s Eastern Hub,
which includes prices from  New Jersey  and Virginia, rose 8.8
percent to $53.93 a megawatt-hour. The premium for Eastern hub
on-peak power versus PJM’s benchmark Western hub narrowed to
$2.23 a megawatt-hour from $26.81 yesterday.  Prices for power on the grid operated by the Electric
Reliability Council of Texas Inc. rose 3.7 percent to $33.03 a
megawatt-hour for the hour ending at 1 p.m. local time.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Mario Parker at 
